Proposed function for increase and decrease of Parasitemy - combines short term logistic growth with long term exponential decline.

\[f(x | \alpha, \beta, \kappa, x_0) = {\kappa e^{-\beta x} \over 1 + (\kappa- x_0)e^{-\alpha x}}\]

But we parameterize this model so that instead of \(\kappa\), the third parameter is \(\chi\) which is the the time at which the curve peaks.

f.chizh <- function(x, alpha, beta, chi, x0){
  kappa <- (x0*alpha + exp(alpha * chi)*beta - x0 * beta)/(alpha - beta)
  kappa/(1 + ((kappa - x0)/x0)*exp(-alpha*x)) * exp(-beta*x)
}

Here?s an example:

x.peak <- function(alpha, beta, kappa, x0){
  log((alpha *  kappa - beta * kappa - alpha * x0 + beta * x0)/beta)/alpha
}

f1 <- finch %>% subset(Experiment == "Exp_1")
{
  plot(Parasitemy ~ dpi, data = f1)
  a <- .3; b <- .15; k = 500; x0 = 1
  curve(4*f.chizh(x, x0 = x0, chi = 25, alpha = a, beta = b), 
        add = TRUE, col = "red", lwd = 2, n = 1e3)
  #abline(v = x.peak(a,b,k,x0), col = "green", lwd =3)
}

Here we fit this to Experiment 1 finches

f1 <- finch %>% subset(Experiment == "Exp_1")
fit1 <- nls(Parasitemy ~ f.chizh(dpi, alpha, beta, chi, x0 = 1), 
           data = f1, 
    start = list(chi = 25, alpha = .3, beta = 0.075), 
    control = list(maxiter=50))
coef1 <- summary(fit1)$coefficients[,1]

f2 <- finch %>% subset(Experiment == "Exp_2")
fit2 <- nls(Parasitemy ~ f.chizh(dpi, alpha, beta, chi, x0 = 1), 
           data = f2, 
    start = list(chi = 25, alpha = .3, beta = 0.075), 
    control = list(maxiter=1000))


coef2 <- summary(fit2)$coefficients[,1]

{
  plot(Parasitemy ~ dpi, data = f1, col = "blue", pch = 19)
  points(Parasitemy ~ dpi, data = f2, col = "red", pch = 19)
  curve(f.chizh(x, x0 = 1, chi = coef1["chi"], 
                alpha = coef1["alpha"], beta = coef1["beta"]), 
        add = TRUE, col = "darkblue", lwd = 2, n = 1e3)
  curve(f.chizh(x, x0 = 1,chi = coef2["chi"], 
                alpha = coef2["alpha"], beta = coef2["beta"]), 
        add = TRUE, col = "darkred", lwd = 2, n = 1e3)
}
